<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78569#p78569</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78569#p78569"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Repairing front-loading NES console cartridge slot]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78569#p78569"><![CDATA[
Welcome to the world of the front-loading NES. It really is like this all the time, no fix for it.<br />Gambled garphics and random freezes are common, no matter how clean your carts are etc... Contrary to popular belief, it's just bad connexion, not dirt or anything.<br /><br />The only thing that half fixed it was to open your NES, use some safety pin to lift all the connector pins and close back your NES. The pins will make better contact, but you will still have problems occasionally.<br /><br />The only way I had to be able to enjoy a 100% working system is to import a toploader all the way from USA, and AV mod it. Now it works wonders, and the connector ALWAYS work (I'd guess the FC and AV Famicom connector's also works fine like that).<br /><br /> <br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The guy took the cartridge connector from a game genie and basicly built a top-loading NES out of a Toaster.<br /></div><br />I wonder if it was a mistake or if it was really the front loader which is called "toaster". All toaster I've ever seen in my life are top loading, but maybe front loading ones are common in america ??<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Mon May 23, 2011 9:09 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
