<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78457#p78457</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78457#p78457"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Repairing front-loading NES console cartridge slot]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7769&amp;p=78457#p78457"><![CDATA[
My childhood trick for the NES was, after you push the cart down, use your two index fingers and kinda wiggle the cart out a little bit, and point the back end of the cart to the left. That usually solved most connection problems.<br /><br />My other trick was to just use a game genie without any codes. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /><br />As far as garbled graphics, my current front-loading NES has a problem where, if I don't use it for a long time, the graphics just <em>will not</em> work correctly (which also breaks SMB's title screen), and no amount of cleaning/fiddling will fix it. However, after playing some games like normal (despite the glitched graphics), the graphics will fix themselves, and the NES will work fine for months and months. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /><br />Maybe your NES does this too?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=21">Drag</a> — Sat May 21, 2011 6:02 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
